{"id":"2007.12511","submitter":"Jiajun Li","authors":"Jiajun Li and Martin Eckstein","title":"Nonequilibrium steady-state theory of photodoped Mott insulators","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. B 103, 045133 (2021)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.103.045133","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.str-el","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Photodoped states are widely observed in laser-excited Mott insulators, in\nwhich charge excitations are quickly created and can exist beyond the duration\nof the external driving. Despite the fruitful experimental explorations,\ntheoretical studies on the microscopic models face the challenge to\nsimultaneously deal with exponentially separated time scales, especially in\nmulti-band systems, where the long-time behaviors are often well beyond the\nreach of state-of-the-art numerical tools. Here, we address this difficulty by\nintroducing a steady-state description of photodoped Mott insulators using an\nopen-system setup, where the photodoped system is stabilized as a\nnon-equilirium steady-state (NESS) by a weak external driving. Taking advantage\nof the stationarity, we implement and discuss the details of an efficient\nnumerical tool using the steady-state Dynamical Mean-Field Theory (DMFT),\ncombined with the non-crossing approximation (NCA). We demonstrate that these\nstationary photodoped states exhibit the same properties of their transient\ncounterparts, while being solvable with reasonable computational efforts.\nFurthermore, they can be parametrized by just few physical quantities,\nincluding the effective temperature and the density of charge excitations,\nwhich confirms the universal nature of photodoped states indeed independent of\nthe excitation protocols. As a first application, we consider the stationary\nphotodoped states in a two-band Hubbard model with intertwined spin-and-orbital\nordering and find a family of hidden phases unknown from the previous studies,\nimplying an apparently unexplored time regime of the relaxation of the\nintertwined orders.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 24 Jul 2020 13:04:10 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-01-27"}
